[vc_row full_width=&quot;&quot; parallax=&quot;&quot; parallax_image=&quot;&quot; lvca_dark_bg=&quot;&quot;][vc_column width=&quot;1/1&quot;][vc_column_text]There are many articles out there focusing on investment advice tips for the novice investor, some of which are on this very site and/or written by our financial experts, and they’re all worth reading if you want to get a good overview of the investment world and understand some of the essential guidelines. We thought we’d simplify it even further for you with a very comprehensive bullet-point list of top tips for any new investor.

&amp;nbsp;
&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Learning to invest is not something you can learn overnight, it takes time, patience and research.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;You don’t need a fortune to start your investing career, you can do it with as little as $50. Then maybe invest more as you learn a bit more about the industry and the process involved.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Hire a full-service broker until you really understand the whole process.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Try to stay away from stocks which cost less than $10 a share – most companies which are worth investing in usually sell at more than that.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;When you’re starting out, invest only in domestic stocks and mutual funds; don’t overcomplicate things.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Diversification is a viable strategy but don’t diversify too much too soon as it will probably confuse you and blur your focus. Just concentrate on a few stocks and watch them carefully.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Generally speaking: with $10,000 or less invest in 2 or 3 stocks, with $50,000 invest in 4 or 5, and when you have $100,000 or more stick to about 7 or 8 stocks.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Try to stay away from Futures and Options due to their highly speculative nature.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Be prepared to take some losses – they won’t all be winners. However, try to cut your losses at around 10% below the price you bought at.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Don’t get too emotionally attached to your stocks, they’re not your babies.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Try to avoid the more volatile markets, like futures and foreign stocks.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Analyze every transaction and investment and learn from both mistakes and successes.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Learn to conduct both fundamental and technical analysis of companies you are thinking of investing in. Fundamental analysis involves looking at a company’s earnings, profit margins, growth and return on equity, which allows you to narrow your search down to only good quality stocks, while technical analysis involves reading a stock’s price and volume chart; applied together they allow you to invest in quality companies at the right time.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Try to pick stocks from the leading industry sectors since most of the market leaders from the past were in the leading groups, like Technology, Communications, Software, Leisure and Entertainment.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Stocks go up due to large buying, usually by mutual funds.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;When a stock leader breaks out from a sound base, it should go up by around 25% in two months; if it does this in less than four weeks, don’t sell it because it’s bound to go up way more.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;On the day a stock ‘breaks out’, volume (the actual number of shares traded) should increase by at least 50%. The most common pattern of a stock with positive gains is called a “cup with handle” because it resembles a cup if you look at it from the side.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Buy stocks at the “pivot point” (the average of the low, high and closing price from the previous day) and don’t buy at any more than 8% above that price.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Don’t worry so much about ‘buying low’; the best stocks are expensive, but the point is to sell at an even higher price. Stocks which are cheap are generally cheap for a reason.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Use chart price and volume action to determine when a stock has reached its optimum point.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Follow the general market (S&amp;amp;P500, Dow Jones, NASDAQ) even if you have no investments in it due to the fact that 75% of stocks follow trends set in the general market.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;A bear market will cause prices to drop by at least 25% and people refuse to believe that it will ever recover. However, a bull market will usually follow a bear market, and it will be full of opportunities.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;After a period of decline, most indices will attempt to rally (advance in price).&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Technical market indicators are of little value. Using a chart indicator is a good way of determining if the time is right to buy a stock.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Operate in up-trending markets, pick stocks from leading industry groups, and which have strong earnings, high return on equity and increasing profit margins.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;When you buy a stock, buy only half of your desired position at the initial buy point, and then buy more if the price rises by 3% or 4%.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;When a stock shows a major deceleration in growth in its earnings per share over 2 quarters in a row, then it’s time to sell.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;In the stock market… HISTORY REPEATS ITSELF. ALWAYS.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
